Cyclistic

Rene SIlva

2022-06-30

Google Data Analytics Capstone Project: Cyclistic bike-share analysis

About the company

In 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a fleet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime.

Until now, Cyclistic’s marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members.

Cyclistic’s finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, Moreno believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, Moreno believes there is a very good chance to convert casual riders into members. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the company’s future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.

Moreno has assigned you the first question to answer: How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

Business Task

Analyze rider’s usage patterns for marketing membership conversion programs.

Tools: R programming

Dataset: Cyclistic’s historical trip data from May 2021 to May 2022

Remove unncessary columns

all_trips <- all_trips %>% select(-c(start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng))

Rename columns

all_trips <- all_trips %>% rename(trip_id = ride_id, ride_type = rideable_type, start_time = started_at, end_time = ended_at, from_station_name = start_station_name, from_station_id = start_station_id, to_station_name = end_station_name, to_station_id = end_station_id, usertype = member_casual)

Add columns that list the date, month, day, and year of each ride and a “ride_length” column in seconds

all_trips$date <- as.Date(all_trips$start_time)
all_trips$month <- format(as.Date(all_trips$date), "%B")
all_trips$day <- format(as.Date(all_trips$date), "%d")
all_trips$year <- format(as.Date(all_trips$date), "%Y")
all_trips$day_of_week <- weekdays(all_trips$date)
all_trips$ride_length <- difftime(all_trips$end_time,all_trips$start_time)

Convert ride_length column to numeric and to minutes

all_trips$ride_length<- as.numeric(as.character(all_trips$ride_length))

is.numeric(all_trips$ride_length)

all_trips$ride_length <- all_trips$ride_length/60

all_trips$ride_length <- round(all_trips$ride_length, 2)

What does the data say?

The average ride length for a casual rider is approximately 31 minutes and for a member rider, it is about 13 minutes. On average the casual rider is almost riding 2.5 times more minutes than a member rider.

The average ride length for a casual rider is almost consistent throughout the week with an increase during the weekend. The average ride duration for member riders is consistent throughout the week from Monday to Friday at approximately 12 minutes slightly increasing to 14 minutes on Saturday and Sunday.

Even though casual riders ride longer during the weekend they take more weekly trips. Looking at all casual rides, casual rides that occur from Monday to Friday account for approximately 58% of all casual rides. Casual riders enjoy riding during the summer months from June to September as those months account for 58.5% of all casual ride trips. On the other hand, only 44.7% of member total rides occur during the summer months.

The type of bike both user types enjoy using is the classic bike. The classic bike usage is consistent throughout the week and increases on Saturday and Sunday which can be seen as a correlation with both users’ average ride duration.

Each user type has different top ten routes when cycling. There is not one route that overlaps. The top route for casual riders is Streeter Dr & Grand Ave to Street Dr & Grand Ave. The top route for casual riders is near many attractions such as the Navy Pier, the beach, and the Chicago Children’s Discover museum. Casual riders may be renting these bikes for the day and riding them around nearby attractions and returning them where they originally rented them.

The top route for member riders is Ellis Ave & 60th St To University Ave & 57th St. This route is nearby the University of Chicago, UChicago Law School, and the UChicago Hospital. On average it takes a member 5.5 minutes to complete the route. Members of Cyclistic can be working professionals or students who need a quick ride across campus or their workplace.

Step 5: Recommendations

The marketing team sould focus on the top 10 routes for casual members during the summer months and have more bikes available in those areas. Also the marketing team can run a promotion that entails casual users to ride two days in a row and get their third day half off.

Members do not use docked bikes, they either choose an electric or classic bike. Docked bikes are also the least used bike for casual riders thus it might be smart to stop the production of docked bikes.

Promote the health benefits of riding a bike as a campaign and track the calories lost while riding as in-app feature. Also include what-if scenarios where one can see how many calories they could burn if they cycle a different route, which will promote riders to try it. In addition, once they burn a certain amount of calories one could get a percentage off a membership.

Overall members and casual riders differ in how long and how often they use the bikes. When one has a membership they can receive a discount for longer rides. In addition Cyclistic can provide a mileage rewards program.
